WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.120
Up next, we have Joe Roberts.

00:00:03.120 --> 00:00:09.320
Joe Roberts Hi, I'm Joe, I am a product manager at Posit,

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:13.320
and I'm going to talk today about taking CRAN to the next level with Posit Public Package

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:14.320
Manager.

00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:17.719
But first, let's talk a bit about who is Posit, because we throw this around, you hear the

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:22.240
name, we've made a few, you know, we fund or support a few of these packages you probably

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:23.860
have heard of.

00:00:23.860 --> 00:00:26.719
Our mission at Posit is to create open source software for data science.

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:31.780
And that's, you know, to make everyone in this room's lives easier.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:35.400
We want to make those free to the data science community, so we give them away.

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:38.759
But we have to fund that somehow, which is through commercial products designed for teams

00:00:38.759 --> 00:00:41.840
and organizations, which is the side of the company that I work on.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.439
But one of those that is based on that is, let's talk about CRAN.

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:47.439
You all know and love CRAN.

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:52.680
Whether you know it or not, you know, CRAN is the official home for over 20,000 packages.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:56.919
And in my earnest belief, the biggest reason ours has become so popular for data science

00:00:56.919 --> 00:00:58.500
is because of CRAN.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:01.959
It is because you have all these packages there that really can solve everything that

00:01:01.959 --> 00:01:04.839
you could possibly want to do and do really cool things.

00:01:04.839 --> 00:01:08.160
And installing packages just works with installed packages.

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:11.720
But there's some better ways to do things even with CRAN.

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:17.540
What we have, one of the products we have on Posit is what we have called a Posit Public

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:22.699
Package Manager, or the three P's and the M, so P3M for shorthand often.

00:01:22.699 --> 00:01:27.580
And so that's a free hosted service that we provide now based on our commercial Posit

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:32.419
Package Manager product that we sell for our enterprise customers.

00:01:32.419 --> 00:01:36.860
But most importantly for this audience, it provides everything in a complete CRAN mirror

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:41.459
like you are already using, plus many additional features that can make it a really useful

00:01:41.459 --> 00:01:42.459
way to help you out.

00:01:42.459 --> 00:01:45.220
It's used widely already in our community.

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:49.980
We serve over 40 million package installs each month from Posit Public Package Manager.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:53.180
And here's some of the reasons that people like it.

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:57.379
For one thing, if you're on Windows or Mac, you probably know the power of binary packages.

00:01:57.379 --> 00:02:00.779
That's why when you install a package from CRAN, you don't have to worry about taking

00:02:00.779 --> 00:02:04.300
the time to actually compile the package and install it that way.

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:07.739
We also provide similar binaries if you are one of those people that's working on Linux

00:02:07.739 --> 00:02:12.979
or in an environment like a Docker container that needs a Linux package.

00:02:12.979 --> 00:02:15.899
So binaries are a huge advantage from there.

00:02:15.899 --> 00:02:21.339
Most importantly, too, CRAN itself builds binary packages for both the current version

00:02:21.339 --> 00:02:25.580
of R and the one previous version of R. We actually go four previous versions of R back

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:28.860
because there are some reasons you still need to use older versions of R and still have

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:36.619
that same level of ease of use, even though you're not on the latest there.

00:02:36.619 --> 00:02:41.960
Similarly, CRAN has one view that is the latest version of every package.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:46.880
We actually have been since about 2018 and taking full snapshots of CRAN every day.

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:52.199
So we actually have the whole history of CRAN for the last six plus years now.

00:02:52.199 --> 00:02:55.160
And so there are the reasons, sometimes the case, you know, you come back to a project

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:59.639
that you started, you know, you were working on an R two years ago and go, oh, I need to

00:02:59.639 --> 00:03:03.600
rebuild this, but I don't have my machine, I'm on a new machine, I need to be able to

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:07.600
get all this here, but the packages that have changed, maybe they've changed in a way that

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:09.699
makes my old code not work the same.

00:03:09.699 --> 00:03:14.100
So with using public package manager here, you can go and say, I want to, instead of

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:18.000
installing all the current packages, I want you to install the versions of all these packages

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.460
that were available two years ago when I worked on this project.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:21.899
So I know that that's what I use then.

00:03:21.899 --> 00:03:26.059
I can then rebuild, get things working again, and then figure out if I want to upgrade and

00:03:26.059 --> 00:03:27.699
keep going from there as well.

00:03:27.699 --> 00:03:31.779
And you can, of course, then use our UI in there to search and view package information

00:03:31.779 --> 00:03:33.339
about all these packages on CRAN.

00:03:33.339 --> 00:03:37.380
Here's a look at a typical, you know, one of those things you might find there.

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:41.419
We actually have details, you can view, kind of drill down, search for packages, see all

00:03:41.419 --> 00:03:47.059
the more details about that, as well as, you know, the versions, and even, we actually

00:03:47.059 --> 00:03:50.619
even just have added security vulnerability checks for those who are on the security conscious

00:03:50.619 --> 00:03:54.059
side, want to make sure that the packages you're using haven't had any sort of security

00:03:54.059 --> 00:03:57.139
issues with them as well.

00:03:57.139 --> 00:04:00.580
Switching over to using public package manager as your CRAN repository is very simple.

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:01.580
We try to keep it that way.

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:05.979
It's a matter of just either changing your options, repos variable in your R session,

00:04:05.979 --> 00:04:06.979
whatever that is.

00:04:06.979 --> 00:04:11.740
If you're using our fabulous R studio, you can just do it right in the, there's a setting

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:12.740
in the UI.

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:16.660
You can just plug it in there and see what you, the URL that you need there.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:20.619
And you can get details specifically for your environment on our setup page.

00:04:20.619 --> 00:04:24.459
You just go to our website, hit the setup button, it'll walk you through exactly everything

00:04:24.459 --> 00:04:25.619
you have to do.

00:04:25.619 --> 00:04:29.299
And our website, of course, to make it simple to write, p3m.dev.

00:04:29.299 --> 00:04:30.299
Check it out, try it today.

00:04:30.299 --> 00:04:33.179
Drop us a note and let us know how you like it, if there's anything you like there.

00:04:33.179 --> 00:04:34.459
And thanks for your time.

